page.title: 01Blakeney Morston & District
page.content: Open farmland rising from salt marshes to about 150 feet. Barley, sugar beet, horticultural crops in huge fields, some grazing of cattle and sheep. Limitless skyscapes over farms and sea. Flint houses, red pantiled roofs and white paint, sailing birdwatching; much visited in summer, deserted save for residents in winter. Farmers and farmworkers, fishermen, shopkeepers, ferrymem, ships handlers, retired residents, some employed in precision engineering and some commuting to nearby towns and those employed in the tourist trade. The villages dominated by their large medieval churches. The marshes liable to flood at spring tides, nature reserves for plants and birds largely owned by the National trust.
